// Hades web UI — event-driven session core.
//
// The original core was turn-based (read a browser command, pump DAP to the
// next stop). That can't do terminal stdin or Pause: while the debuggee runs,
// the session is blocked reading DAP — exactly when those arrive. So every
// session is split into cooperating green tasks with single-owner IO:
//
//   WS-reader  (R) — owns WsConn.recv. Browser commands dispatched immediately:
//                    stdin → pty master; everything else → DAP requests (ODD seqs).
//   DAP-reader (D) — owns DapClient.recv. Events/responses → WS pushes (EVEN
//                    seqs for its own requests); handles runInTerminal reverse
//                    requests by spawning the debuggee in a std/pty.
//   WS-writer  (W) — the ONLY task that writes the socket. Fed by a
//                    Channel<string> + self-pipe wake (Channel.recv would
//                    pthread_cond_wait and stall the whole green scheduler).
//   PTY pump   (P) — pty master → WS "ptyData".
//
// Concurrency invariants (all yield-point reasoning; scheduler is cooperative):
//   * DAP frames are written with a single write() (see framing.milo), so R's
//     and D's requests can't interleave; odd/even seq split means no collisions.
//   * All WS sends funnel through W, so WS frames can't interleave either.
//   * Channels are drained with tryRecv only — never a blocking recv on the
//     scheduler thread.
//
// Run: hades-web --program /tmp/hades_demo --source /tmp/hades_demo.c [--port 8080]

